  "summary": "Colonel Korduk interrogates Mrs. Hammers regarding her husband, whom she claims she has not seen in years. Korduk suggests that her husband was actually a deserter living under a different identity and implies she may have recently met him in a gazebo. Although Mrs. Hammers denies these claims, Korduk remains convinced she is lying. He notes that while Captain Himmelman has a tarnished military record, he is unlikely to be responsible for the oil found on a door, suggesting the culprit is someone within the house.\n\nSearching the attic, Korduk discovers trunks of clothing and a small briefcase belonging to Charlotte Blacklock, the deceased sister of Letitia Blacklock. Inside the briefcase are old letters written by Letitia to Charlotte, which reveal Letitia's deep affection for her sister, who had suffered from a disfigurement. Korduk hopes these documents might provide clues regarding Sonia Goddard. When he asks to take the letters, Letitia reacts with anger and frustration, calling them private. She eventually relents, telling him to burn them after reading, and expresses fear that the killer might target young people like Patrick, Julia, Philly, or Micky.\n\nThe following day, Korduk visits Miss Marple at the parsonage. He shows her one of the letters to gain insight into the mindset of that generation, describing the Blacklock family's father, Dr. Blacklock, as a stubborn and self-righteous man.",
